        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We will use a single pointing centred on the HDF-South QSO. The field of view for band 4 and our selected frequency is 39", or a region up to ~170 proper kpc from the QSO sightline. This is a large enough field of view to detect the galaxy counterparts to the absorbers, which are expected to be associated on scales of 20-150 kpc. We have chosen the central frequency of baseband 1 to cover the expected positions of CO 4-3 for both absorbers at a spectral resolution of 2 km/s. We place baseband 2 to cover the CO 4-3 at the redshift of the background QSO at a lower ~8 km/s resolution to keep the data rate below the limit of 16MB/s. This will be used to study CO emission associated with the CO host galaxy, and explore nature of the ~100 kpc Lya nebulae surrounding the QSO. The remaining two basebands bands cover continuum regions.

The precise CO luminosity of the absorbing galaxies is unknown. However, the characteristic Schechter CO luminosity at z=1.93 is ~10^10 K km/s pc^-2 based on theoretical models and a blind search at these redshifts. We expect the galaxies corresponding to each of the Lyman limit systems to be ~L*, based on theoretical predictions for the contribution of such galaxies to the absorption cross-section of Lyman limit systems (Fumagalli et al 2011), and on the presence of metal-enriched gas on one of the absorbers. To maximise the probability of a detection and still result in a reasonable integration time, we aim to detect a line luminosity of 10^9.2 K km/s pc^-2. This corresponds to 0.5 Jy km/s at z=1.93, assuming a Planck 2013 cosmology, and that we use the CO 4-3 line, which falls inside ALMA band 4. If we assume a linewidth of 150 km/s, which is typical of the virial velocities of our target galaxies, and a conversion (CO 4-3) = 0.3*(CO 1-0), we find that a 3-sigma detection limit of 0.09 mJy is required to detect such a line. Using the exposure time calculator, we find a requirement of 2.6h on source, or 5.35h when overheads are included.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
